<span id="ix.ix.vii"></span>

#### <span id="ix.ix.vii-p0.1"></span>Elucidations.

##### <span id="ix.ix.vii-p0.2"></span>I.

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p1"></span>(The Bidding Prayer, etc., p. 485.)  

#### <span id="ix.ix.vii-p1.2"></span>The Pauline Norm. <span id="fr_3826"></span>[3827](#fn_3826.md)

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p3"></span>1. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p3.1"></span>Supplications.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p4"></span>2. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p4.1"></span>Prayers, Psalms, Hymns, and Spiritual Songs.
 

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p5"></span>3. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p5.1"></span>Intercessions.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p6"></span>4. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p6.1"></span>General Thanksgiving. The Kiss of Peace.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p7"></span>5. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p7.1"></span>Anaphora. <span
id="fr_3827"></span>[3828](#fn_3827.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p9"></span>The Lord <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p9.1"></span>Jesus the same night in which He was betrayed
took bread:  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p10"></span>And when He had given thanks, He brake
it,  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p11"></span>And said, Take, eat: this is my Body,
which is broken for you:  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p12"></span>This do in remembrance of Me.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p13"></span>After the same manner also He took the
cup, when He had supped,  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p14"></span>Saying, This cup is the New Testament in
my Blood:  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p15"></span>This do ye, as oft as ye drink it, in
remembrance of Me.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p16"></span>For as often as ye eat this Bread, and
drink this Cup, ye do show the Lord’s death till He come.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p17"></span>6. <span id="ix.ix.vii-p17.1"></span>Our
Father, etc. <span id="fr_3828"></span>[3829](#fn_3828.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p19"></span>7. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p19.1"></span>Communion.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p20"></span>Let us note also that the Apostle had
“delivered” unto the Corinthians ([1 Cor. xi.
23](../../../bib/kjv/co1011.htm#023)<span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.1"></span>.md),
as doubtless to others ([1 Cor. vii.
17](../../../bib/kjv/co1007.htm#017)<span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.2"></span>.md),
certain institutions which he <span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.3"></span>ordained
in all the churches, and for departing from which he censures the
Corinthians in this place ([I Cor. vii.
17](../../../bib/kjv/co1007.htm#017.md)<span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.4"></span>
compared with [I Cor. vii. 2](../../../bib/kjv/co1007.htm#002.md)<span
id="ix.ix.vii-p20.5"></span>) in certain particulars. In chap. [I Cor.
xiv. 40.](../../../bib/kjv/co1014.htm#040.md)<span
id="ix.ix.vii-p20.6"></span>, he refers to these ordinances as a <span
class="Greek"><span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.7"></span>τα</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.8"></span>́</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="ix.ix.vii-p20.9"></span>ξις</span>, in the
performance of which they were to proceed (<span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p20.10"></span>κοσμι</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p20.11"></span>́</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p20.12"></span>ως</span>) with due order, <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p20.13"></span>becomingly; not with mere decency, but with
a beautiful decorum of service.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p21"></span>Finally, let me suggest that there are
fragments of the Apostle’s (<span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p21.1"></span>παρα</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p21.2"></span>́</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p21.3"></span>δοσεις</span>) instructions everywhere
scattered through his Epistles, such as the minute canon <span
id="fr_3829"></span>[3830](#fn_3829.md) concerning the veiling of women in
acts of worship, insisting upon it with a length of argument which in
one of the Apostolic Fathers would be considered childish. He also
insisted that his <span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p22.2"></span>τα</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p22.3"></span>́</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p22.4"></span>ξις</span> is from the Lord. <span
id="page_507">p. 507</span> <span id="ix.ix.vii-Page_507"></span>  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p23"></span>Fragments of the primitive hymns are
also scattered through the Apostles’ writings, as, e.g.,—  

> <span id="ix.ix.vii-p23.1"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
> id="ix.ix.vii-p23.3"></span>́Εγειραι ὁ καθεύδων,</span>  
> <span class="Greek"><span id="ix.ix.vii-p23.5"></span>καὶ ἀνάστα ἐκ
> τω̑ν νεκρω̑ν</span>  
> <span class="Greek"><span id="ix.ix.vii-p23.7"></span>καὶ ἐπιφαύσει
> σοι ὀ Χριστός.</span> <span id="fr_3830"></span>[3831](#fn_3830.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p25"></span>Of such passages the formula (<span
class="Greek"><span id="ix.ix.vii-p25.1"></span>διὸ λέγει</span>) “It
saith” seems to be a frequent index.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p26"></span>May we not conclude also that the
sublime prayer and doxology of [Eph. iii.
14-21](../../../bib/kjv/eph003.htm#014.md)<span
id="ix.ix.vii-p26.1"></span> is a quotation from the Apostle’s own
eucharistic <span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p26.2"></span>τάξις</span> for the whole state of Christ’s
Church militant?  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p27"></span>Might not the same be more constantly
used in our days as an intercession for the whole flock of the one
Shepherd?  

##### <span id="ix.ix.vii-p27.1"></span>II.

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p28"></span>(Fulfil His constitution, p. 489.)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p29"></span>The Pauline Norm being borne in mind, we
shall best comprehend this <span id="ix.ix.vii-p29.1"></span>Clementine
liturgy, as to its primitive claims, by taking the testimony of <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p29.2"></span>Justin, writing in Rome to the Antonines
<span id="ix.ix.vii-p29.3"></span>a. d.160. Referring to the <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p29.4"></span>Apology in our first volume, we observe that
the order kept up in his day was this:—  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p30"></span>1. Prayers for all estates of men.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p31"></span>2. The kiss of peace.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p32"></span>3. Oblation of bread and wine.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p33"></span>4. Thanksgiving.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p34"></span>5. Words of institution.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p35"></span>6. The prayer ending with <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p35.1"></span>Amen.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p36"></span>7. Communion.  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p37"></span>Now, a century later, we may suppose the
<span id="ix.ix.vii-p37.1"></span>original of this <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p37.2"></span>Clementine to have taken a fuller shape; of
which still later this <span id="ix.ix.vii-p37.3"></span>Clementine is
the product. <span id="fr_3831"></span>[3832](#fn_3831.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p39"></span>Bear in mind that the early Roman use
was (Greek) borrowed wholly from the East; <span
id="fr_3832"></span>[3833](#fn_3832.md) and, comparing the testimony of
<span id="ix.ix.vii-p40.3"></span>Justin with the Pauline Norm, may we
not suppose that this norm in Rome was augmented by the <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p40.4"></span>Eastern uses, and so preserves a true name
in that of the first Bishop of Rome, who accepted it from Jerusalem or
Antioch?  

##### <span id="ix.ix.vii-p40.5"></span>III.

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p41"></span>(That He may show this bread, etc., p.
489.)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p42"></span>From a recent essay by Dr. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p42.1"></span>Williams, the erudite bishop of Connecticut,
I am permitted to cite, as follows:—  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p43"></span>  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p44"></span>Compare the original texts thus:—  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p45"></span><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p45.1"></span>Clementine. <span
id="fr_3833"></span>[3834](#fn_3833.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p47"></span><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p47.1"></span>Irenæus. <span
id="fr_3834"></span>[3835](#fn_3834.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p49"></span>  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p50"></span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p50.1"></span>ὀπως αποφηνῃ τοὸν ὰρτον του̑τον σω̑μα του̑
Χριστου̑ σου καὶ τὸ ποτήριον του̑τον αἰμα του̑ Χριστου̑ σου ινα οἱ
μεταλαβόντες, κ.τ.λ.</span>  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p51"></span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p51.1"></span>ὅ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p51.2"></span>πως ἀποφηνῃ τὴν θυσίαν ταύτην, καὶ τὸν ἄ́ρτον
σω̑μα του̑ Χριστου̑, καὶ τὸ ποτήριον τὸ αἰμα του̑ Χριστου̑ ἴνα οἱ
μεταλαβόντες, κ.τ.λ.</span>  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p52"></span><span id="page_508">p. 508</span> <span
id="ix.ix.vii-Page_508"></span>  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p53"></span>Bishop <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p53.1"></span>Williams then proceeds to inquire:—  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p54"></span> “How is this striking agreement to be
explained? Does <span id="ix.ix.vii-p54.1"></span>Irenæus quote from the
Clementine, or the Clementine from him? Or is it not much more likely
that they are independent witnesses to primitive uses, going back to the
period of the persecutions, and extending far beyond the limits of Syria
or Palestine’?” <span id="fr_3835"></span>[3836](#fn_3835.md)  

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p56"></span>I shall recur to these passages in the
elucidations to <span id="ix.ix.vii-p56.1"></span>Early Liturgies (<span
id="ix.ix.vii-p56.2"></span>infra): but here I beg the reader to consult
<span id="ix.ix.vii-p56.3"></span>Pfaff, to whom we owe the discovery of
the fragment cited from <span id="ix.ix.vii-p56.4"></span>Irenæus; also
<span id="ix.ix.vii-p56.5"></span>Grabe, in the same volume of <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p56.6"></span>Pfaff, whom I have already introduced to the
reader. <span id="fr_3836"></span>[3837](#fn_3836.md)  

##### <span id="ix.ix.vii-p57.5"></span>Postscript.

<span id="ix.ix.vii-p58"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="ix.ix.vii-p58.1"></span>The</span> American editor had been promised
the aid of his beloved friend the Rev. Dr. <span
id="ix.ix.vii-p58.2"></span>Hobart in the elucidation of the liturgies;
but a sudden and almost fatal prostration of his health has deprived the
reader of the admirable comments with which he would have enriched these
pages, had Providence permitted.  

